    <question>
        <prompt>The fundamentalist movement of the 1920s represented:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Support for modernism</option>
            <option letter="b">Religious resistance to cultural change</option>
            <option letter="c">Scientific advancement</option>
            <option letter="d">Political reform</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The fundamentalist movement represented religious resistance to cultural change in 1920s America. Fundamentalists defended traditional Protestant beliefs against modernist challenges, opposed the teaching of evolution, advocated literal interpretation of the Bible, and resisted changing social values. This movement exemplified the broader cultural conflict between tradition and modernity in the 1920s.</explanation>
